fields.neighborhood_overview: El Raval is a neighbourhood in the Ciutat Vella district of Barcelona, Spain. The area, especially the part closest to the port, was also informally known as Barri Xinès or Barrio Chino, meaning "Chinatown". El Raval is one of the two historical neighborhoods that border La Rambla, the other being the Barri Gòtic, and contains some 50,000 people. An area historically infamous for its nightlife and cabarets, as well as prostitution and crime, El Raval has changed significantly in recent years and due to its central location has become a minor attraction of Barcelona. The northern border of the neighborhood is marked by Plaça Catalunya and Plaça Universitat, and the street which connects them, Carrer de Pelai. It ends in the east with La Rambla, and in the west and south, the neighborhood is delimited by Ronda Sant Antoni, Ronda Sant Pau and Avinguda del Paral·lel. fields.host_about: Hello, my name is Pablo and I work in a restaurant and coffee-shop, although I've studied art because that's my true passion. I also love music, literature, cinema, and scientific fields such as biology, zoology and botany. I love gardening, and when travelling I visit botanical gardens as well as art museums. I think my house is a reflection of my own interests and tastes, and I hope you will enjoy it and care for it as I do. I’m happy to have the possibility of renting my flat from time to time. For me it’s a great responsibility to receive travellers from all over the world, because I want them to feel comfortable and to offer them a clean, tidy, warm and practical space where they can feel at home. As I’m giving you the keys to my own house, I expect maximum care to be taken by my guests and a most respectful attitude toward the neighbours, avoiding any loud music or noises (especially at night, but also in daylight hours) that could disturb their peace.
